{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a7408ba-e535-449e-9426-22481620473e","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the page not to add padding, but you likely also need to:\n\n1. **Make the system bars transparent** so content is actually visible behind them.\n2. **Set `IgnoreSafeArea`** on the view itself (especially needed on iOS).\n\nHere's a typical approach:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThen in your platform setup, ensure transparent system bars:\n\n**Android** — in `MainActivity.cs` or via your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n```csharp\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n```\n\nOr in `Platforms/Android/Resources/values/styles.xml`:\n```xml\n<item name=\"android:statusBarColor\">@android:color/transparent</item>\n<item name=\"android:navigationBarColor\">@android:color/transparent</item>\n```\n\n**iOS** — `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the Image (or its parent layout) is usually sufficient since the status bar is always translucent.\n\n**Key gotcha on .NET 10 + Android 15 (API 35):** Edge-to-edge is enforced by the OS, so `SetStatusBarColor` is ignored — bars are already transparent. If you still see gaps, the issue is almost certainly that `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` is missing on the view, or a parent `Grid`/`VerticalStackLayout` is itself being padded. Make sure the image (or its direct container) has `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2967eed3-b2ec-4601-b24d-3d46d93cf4b5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10, specifically wanting an image to go behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still have padding.\n\nThis is a question about .NET MAUI's edge-to-edge/safe area handling. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, particularly with newer versions targeting Android 15+ and .NET 9+, there have been changes to how edge-to-edge display works. \n\nKey points:\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on ContentPage tells the page not to automatically pad content away from safe areas.\n\n\n2. On Android 15+, apps run edge-to-edge by default, but the system still applies window insets that need to be handled separately.\n3. iOS requires similar handling through safe area properties.\n\nFor .NET 10, the edge-to-edge behavior on Android is enforced, so beyond setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page, the user likely needs to also use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on individual views like the image to prevent them from being inset by the system. this with `SafeAreaEdges`. Setting it to `None` removes the automatic safe area padding, though I might also need to handle transparent status and navigation bars on Android, or deal with interference from Shell or NavigationPage wrappers. The core solution is likely `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` combined with making the system bars transparent where needed.","outputTokens":1374,"requestId":"981D:15979F:1668A64:1912725:6A052176"},"id":"6f8776e2-c398-4712-aecc-546754af3a5a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:12:50.322Z","parentId":"fb5638b4-8d8a-4eac-980d-7604a32a5317"}
